{
  "texts": [
    "Studies have found that LLM-generated tests are riddled with test smells, and these poor design choices hinder readability and long-term maintenance.",
    "The most prevalent smells are \"magic number test\" (hard-coded constants in assertions) and \"assertion roulette\" (multiple unexplained assertions in a single test method).",
    "The former was found in 100% of generated tests in a study on HPC projects [76,127], and its prevalence also approached 100% in another large-scale study on Java projects [102], while the latter appeared in over 50% of tests generated using simple zero-shot prompting [104].",
    "Fortunately, evidence suggests that some smells can be mitigated by advanced prompt engineering techniques such as guided Tree of Thoughts, which reduced the incidence of Assertion Roulette from 54.77% to 20.94% [104].",
    "Furthermore, recent work has explored using LLMs to automatically refactor generated tests to eliminate smells."
  ]
}